Figure 1Extracellular mineral bearing vesicles observed with cryo-SEM, upper panel in lens detector, lower panel BSE detector. (A) Overview of the trabecular channel within the cortical bone (CB). (B) Magnification of area depicted by yellow dotted box in (A). Two layers of bone cells potentially osteoblasts (Obs) lining the cortical bone trabecula. The borders of the bone cell layer are depicted by the yellow dotted line. Mineral-bearing vesicles are observed inside the bone cell (white arrow head) and within the extracellular space (ECS) depicted by the yellow arrowhead. (C) Higher magnification of the extracellular mineral-bearing vesicle. Scale bars: (A) 20 μm; (B) 4 μm; (C) 1 μm.Suppl. Video 1FIB-SSV image stack showing the interface between the blood vessel and the mineralizing bone structures. The stack is composed of 497 images spanning a total thickness of approximately 10 μm. Membrane bound mineral particles observed in different tissues are depicted with colored arrowheads. Note that membrane-bound mineral particles inside osteoblasts are only faintly visible due to insufficient contrast. However some of mineral particle-bearing organelles often reminiscent of mitochondrial networks are exemplarily marked by red arrowheads. These structures are recognized as brighter tubular networks within the osteoblasts.Supplementary data to this article can be found online at http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.bone.2015.10.009.
